    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-11-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-11-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="721"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d721">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">762.9411/188</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Butler</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Adviser on Political delations</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hornbeck</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-11-20">November 20,
                            1940</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Dr. Hornbeck</hi>: Below is the text of the telegram,
                    dated November 19th, addressed to the Foreign Office by His Majesty’s Ambassador
                    at Chungking, of which you told me this morning that you would be glad to have a
                    copy.</p>
                <quote rend="blockquote">
                    <p>“Yesterday Chiang Kai Shek told me in strict confidence that immediately
                        after Molotoff’s visit to Berlin Ribbentrop had sent for the Chinese
                            Ambassador<note n="97" xml:id="d721fn97">Chen Chieh.</note> and had made
                        a statement to him in the following sense.</p>
                    <p>Germany now controlled the whole of Europe (Italy was not mentioned). War
                        would be over by the end of this year or at the latest early spring. China
                        was advised to make early peace with Japan and to join the Axis. This was
                        her last chance of admission to the fold. If she refused to make peace Japan
                        would recognise Wang Ching Wei and Italy would follow her example. In these
                        circumstances it would be impossible for Germany to refrain from acting in
                        concert with her allies.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>Yours sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nevile Butler</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
